{
  "doc_id": "27367",
  "text": "In the past few years, the matching literature in economics has developed a comparative stream, examining whether cross-national variation in the supply and demand of university graduates affects the rate of overeducation (e.g., [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . In sociology, an important line of comparative research has been optimistic about the consequences of vocational education and training (VET) systems that have a strong focus on occupationspecific skills. According to this literature, movement from the educational system to the labor market typically runs more smoothly in systems with a strong VET sector, such as Germany, Switzerland, or the Netherlands [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Indeed, studies find lower youth-to-adult unemployment rates [CITATION_5] , higher entry rates into skilled trades among school leavers with medium-level qualifications [CITATION_6] , and a more limited tendency for credential inflation without corresponding labor market benefits (Aizenman et al. 2018) in countries with a strong VET system. Comparative studies also show that the \"quality\" of employment in terms of occupational status and stable careers is more strongly related to educational qualifications in countries with well-developed VET systems [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] .",
